sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_M1207
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: Temperature Sensitive Hairpin Loop + Tet Repressor
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Consists of a sequence that codes for a temperature sensitive mRNA strand, which forms a hairpin stem and loop structure, occluding the Shine-Delgarno sequence that allows tranlation. At 42 degrees Celsius the hydrogen bonds between the self-complimentary pairs are broken and the subsequent protein, a Tet-repressor, can be translated. This part is regulated by a RecA promoter. This part functions as a switch that regulates cell survival, making them viable only above 42 degrees.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Aaron Winder

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K115001
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This part is designed as a temperature inducible RBS. Only designed so far.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: O.M.J.A. Stassen
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: This sequence is taken from the Bradirhizobium Japonicum (BA000040.) as the 5'UTR (ROSE) of a heat shock protein (prfA).
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: The secondary structure is important to the function of these regions, but part of the wt secondary structure is destroyed by the scar. We've tried to alter the sequence so the predicted structure (through mfold and those kind of servers) is sort of conserved, but temperature sensitivity still has to be tested. If it doesn't work, possible solution might be the addition of a larger conserved part of the wt, which implies a small part of wt protein sequence as well.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: tetR
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Coding region for the TetR protein without the Ribosome Binding Site. Modified with an LVA tail for rapid degradation of the protein and faster fall time for the emission. TetR binds to the pTet regulator (BBa_R0040). aTc (anhydrotetracycline) binds to TetR and inhibits its operation.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: June Rhee, Connie Tao, Ty Thomson, Louis Waldman.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Elowitz, M. B. Transport, Assembly, and Dynamics in Systems of Interacting Proteins. Thesis, Princeton Univ., Princeton (1999)

BBa_C0040 TetR Protein is based on the TetR sequence from Elowitz's repressilator. It has been modified to include a rapid degradation LVA tail, and includes the BioBrick standard assembly head and tail restriction sites. The RBS has been removed. The stop codon has been changed from TAA to a double stop codon TAATAA.
